each other, is not defined! That’s why the following four depictions can all be considered equivalent, as the network structure (topology) is identical in all four cases.","position":{"start":{"line":5,"column":1},"end":{"line":5,"column":1}},"key":"Y38KCBYhWQ"}],"key":"MRJaTN80lh"},{"type":"container","kind":"figure","children":[{"type":"image","url":"/build/fig_graph_layout_int-1fcb0495562df993cf0eba2e43505de1.png","alt":"Graphs are based on nodes and their connections (links/edges). But in nearly all cases, this does not fully determine the position of the nodes.","data":{"altTextIsAutoGenerated":true},"key":"gVOiXMgs9K","urlSource":"../images/fig_graph_layout_intro.png"},{"type":"caption","children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":10,"column":1},"end":{"line":10,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"captionNumber","kind":"figure","label":"fig_graph_layouts01","identifier":"fig_graph_layouts01","html_id":"fig-graph-layouts01","enumerator":"1","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Figure ","key":"TYZQtuAaqi"},{"type":"text","value":"1","key":"igRhzRy1Si"},{"type":"text","value":":","key":"cBuUEtc2YL"}],"template":"Figure %s:","key":"ynJmIvbRfG"},{"type":"text","value":"Graphs are based on nodes and their connections (links/edges). But in nearly all cases, this does not fully determine the position of the nodes.","position":{"start":{"line":10,"column":1},"end":{"line":10,"column":1}},"key":"ZeIKBuEk8u"}],"key":"V9Evcsgbpr"}],"key":"PApKBIxGCw"}],"label":"fig_graph_layouts01","identifier":"fig_graph_layouts01","enumerator":"1","html_id":"fig-graph-layouts01","key":"QAqp0PghfM"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":13,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"When we need to visualize a graph, we (or an algorithm) must decide how to arrange the nodes. There are numerous possibilities for this, and the following images show six such network layouts that are included in networkx.","position":{"start":{"line":13,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"key":"PHJOUjKEbU"}],"key":"Be0DK3Wr9u"}],"key":"a6PqiBBC9e"},{"type":"block","kind":"notebook-code","data":{"tags":[]},"children":[{"type":"code","lang":"python","executable":true,"value":"import numpy as np\nimport pandas as pd\nfrom matplotlib import pyplot as plt\n\nimport networkx as nx","visibility":"hide","key":"Aqu9h7N0Rn"},{"type":"outputs","id":"Dpyr1PGhfy35rzaGS1xXt","children":[],"visibility":"show","key":"y6dgNQIPjV"}],"visibility":"show","key":"yELxs17ml7"},{"type":"block","kind":"notebook-code","children":[{"type":"code","lang":"python","executable":true,"value":"nx.layout.__all__","key":"dxOFFvF7VP"},{"type":"outputs","id":"Y7OOhJ19hMsI4_Sy6K4oh","children":[{"type":"output","jupyter_data":{"output_type":"execute_result","execution_count":2,"metadata":{},"data":{"text/plain":{"content":"['bipartite_layout',\n 'circular_layout',\n 'kamada_kawai_layout',\n 'random_layout',\n 'rescale_layout',\n 'rescale_layout_dict',\n 'shell_layout',\n 'spring_layout',\n 'spectral_layout',\n 'planar_layout',\n 'fruchterman_reingold_layout',\n 'spiral_layout',\n 'multipartite_layout',\n 'arf_layout']","content_type":"text/plain"}}},"children":[],"key":"vmfjrarH8k"}],"key":"kScDK7OqHM"}],"key":"ontO4ZJOt1"},{"type":"block","kind":"notebook-code","data":{"tags":[]},"children":[{"type":"code","lang":"python","executable":true,"value":"some_layouts = [nx.layout.circular_layout,\n               nx.layout.kamada_kawai_layout,\n               nx.layout.random_layout,\n               nx.layout.spring_layout,\n               nx.layout.spectral_layout,\n               nx.layout.spiral_layout,\n               ]\n\nG = nx.karate_club_graph()\nfig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 3, figsize=(18, 12))\n\nfor i, func in enumerate(some_layouts):\n    pos = func(G)\n    x = i // 3\n    y = i % 3\n    nx.draw(G, with_labels=True, node_color='teal',\n           pos=pos, ax=axes[x, y], alpha=0.7)\n    axes[x, y].set_title(func.__name__)\n    \nplt.show()","visibility":"hide","key":"jglZJeU7NQ"},{"type":"outputs","id":"BzOgS0U2JQgJOolvYBqTj","children":[{"type":"output","jupyter_data":{"output_type":"display_data","metadata":{},"data":{"image/png":{"content_type":"image/png","hash":"37b11f8dfc1939f76ee7816874e6bed7","path":"/build/37b11f8dfc1939f76ee7816874e6bed7.png"},"text/plain":{"content":"<Figure size 1800x1200 with 6 Axes>","content_type":"text/plain"}}},"children":[],"key":"X6jTXScQub"}],"visibility":"show","key":"UOsXPIYZh3"}],"visibility":"show","key":"hNNdcecJUE"},{"type":"block","kind":"notebook-content","children":[{"type":"heading","depth":3,"position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Add more dimensions to the visualization","position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"key":"BLdOrOVzMa"}],"identifier":"add-more-dimensions-to-the-visualization","label":"Add more dimensions to the visualization","html_id":"add-more-dimensions-to-the-visualization","implicit":true,"key":"G7WPciDmWO"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":2,"column":1},"end":{"line":2,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Inspecting graphs visually is often a great way to get an intuition of the data. Besides node and edge positions, we can add additional information (or attributes) through node labels, node color, but also node size and shape.","position":{"start":{"line":2,"column":1},"end":{"line":2,"column":1}},"key":"dragYHBdq4"}],"key":"tZMU2WZSN1"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":4,"column":1},"end":{"line":4,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"In the following, we will color each node by its degree, i.e., the number of connections each node has.","position":{"start":{"line":4,"column":1},"end":{"line":4,"column":1}},"key":"ZHiDT5iPZQ"}],"key":"OQCda9hOXs"}],"key":"LNuOLfMZwe"},{"type":"block","kind":"notebook-code","data":{"tags":[]},"children":[{"type":"code","lang":"python","executable":true,"value":"some_layouts = [nx.layout.circular_layout,\n               nx.layout.kamada_kawai_layout,\n               nx.layout.random_layout,\n               nx.layout.spring_layout,\n               nx.layout.spectral_layout,\n               nx.layout.spiral_layout,\n               ]\n\nG = nx.karate_club_graph()\nfig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 3, figsize=(18, 12))\n\nfor i, func in enumerate(some_layouts):\n    pos = func(G)\n    x = i // 3\n    y = i % 3\n    nx.draw(G, with_labels=True, node_color=[G.degree(n) for n in G.nodes()],\n           pos=pos, ax=axes[x, y], alpha=0.7)\n    axes[x, y].set_title(func.__name__)\n    \n#plt.savefig(\"networkx_graph_layouts.png\", dpi=200, bbox_inches=\"tight\")\nplt.show()","visibility":"hide","key":"bTEfKmpCXv"},{"type":"outputs","id":"2W6TJ7TcZaHy-EnIocZHQ","children":[{"type":"output","jupyter_data":{"output_type":"display_data","metadata":{},"data":{"image/png":{"content_type":"image/png","hash":"f644628813e7d31524db90d073812841","path":"/build/f644628813e7d31524db90d073812841.png"},"text/plain":{"content":"<Figure size 1800x1200 with 6 Axes>","content_type":"text/plain"}}},"children":[],"key":"fqaDBFA4Wc"}],"visibility":"show","key":"LQ00tanc0l"}],"visibility":"show","key":"ucYiXJ38l6"},{"type":"block","kind":"notebook-content","children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Different layouts have different strengths and weaknesses. A circular arrangement (","position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"key":"hVf8IYVV9q"},{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"circular layout","position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"key":"hG1e20hbMl"}],"key":"ezQNEhs6zq"},{"type":"text","value":") can, for instance, be useful for quickly identifying which nodes have the most connections (and where these lead). Layouts such as random layout or other fixed forms like spirals etc. (as seen above: ","position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"key":"n0EQE0NdoM"},{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"spiral layout","position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"key":"vUedeVjtMh"}],"key":"NRbgCfbxsh"},{"type":"text","value":") are much less commonly used in practice.","position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"key":"cOSwDRaj0O"}],"key":"JXf2XNGJ2l"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The most commonly used layout is a so-called “force-directed” layout (in networkx the ","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"cgQ8yzG1AO"},{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"spring-layout","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"C0l4m5BtvB"}],"key":"kYs0cLQjKR"},{"type":"text","value":", but also the ","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"sAGnEeVF9W"},{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"kamada-kawai-layout","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"D2vU29cJG7"}],"key":"UTvOk3dTj4"},{"type":"text","value":" fall in this category).","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"KjTadiGGMs"}],"key":"bijXTEbxFE"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":5,"column":1},"end":{"line":5,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Force-directed / spring layout","position":{"start":{"line":5,"column":1},"end":{"line":5,"column":1}},"key":"XLTCCldcsM"}],"identifier":"force-directed-spring-layout","label":"Force-directed / spring layout","html_id":"force-directed-spring-layout","implicit":true,"key":"rBW1iQaaLz"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":1},"end":{"line":7,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"In the so-called force-directed layout, links are interpreted as mechanical springs. In a sort of physics simulation, the nodes (connected by the mechanical springs) are then gradually moved depending on the prevailing forces (springs and attractive forces).","position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":1},"end":{"line":7,"column":1}},"key":"sTLzGYQRoX"}],"key":"uj5fFvRdMs"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Depending on the tool, various parameters can be set. Central here is the “strength” and/or “length” of the springs, often expressed as the physical spring constant ","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"key":"U6n1Y5iIZe"},{"type":"inlineMath","value":"k","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"html":"<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">k</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">k</span></span></span></span>","key":"qBkSZrn7xJ"},{"type":"text","value":". This can lead to very different results:","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"key":"szTBK42RsH"}],"key":"LpBvXA7OHq"}],"key":"wyYajZjIFu"},{"type":"block","kind":"notebook-code","data":{"tags":[]},"children":[{"type":"code","lang":"python","executable":true,"value":"G = nx.karate_club_graph()\nfig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 12))\n\nfor i, k in enumerate([0.001, 0.1, 1, 10]):\n    pos = nx.layout.spring_layout(G, k=k)\n    x = i // 2\n    y = i % 2\n    nx.draw(G, with_labels=True, node_color=[G.degree(n) for n in G.nodes()],\n           pos=pos, ax=axes[x, y], alpha=0.7)\n    axes[x, y].set_title(f\"Spring layout, k={k}\")\n\n#plt.savefig(\"networkx_graph_spring_layouts.png\", dpi=200, bbox_inches=\"tight\")    \nplt.show()","visibility":"hide","key":"BblBrRViQE"},{"type":"outputs","id":"p8PzI8Znork5onYJcktC5","children":[{"type":"output","jupyter_data":{"output_type":"display_data","metadata":{},"data":{"image/png":{"content_type":"image/png","hash":"21c04c0d539540f9f22eb04a73b2294c","path":"/build/21c04c0d539540f9f22eb04a73b2294c.png"},"text/plain":{"content":"<Figure size 1200x1200 with 4 Axes>","content_type":"text/plain"}}},"children":[],"key":"cZT8EmRBKe"}],"visibility":"show","key":"cajEO1vx9s"}],"visibility":"show","key":"SyK5vaiQdX"},{"type":"block","kind":"notebook-content","children":[{"type":"heading","depth":3,"position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Visual Randomness","position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"key":"XyPbw8zfjM"}],"identifier":"visual-randomness","label":"Visual Randomness","html_id":"visual-randomness","implicit":true,"key":"OthFenVQrM"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":2,"column":1},"end":{"line":2,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Moreover, even with a set layout type and parameters, there are significant visual variations that result from the random starting positions of the nodes. If we apply the same layout to the same graph multiple times, the results all look different (unless the seed is fixed).","position":{"start":{"line":2,"column":1},"end":{"line":2,"column":1}},"key":"qtijD0getB"}],"key":"xRbSWRn9xe"}],"key":"GUrYAkiKUf"},{"type":"block","kind":"notebook-code","data":{"tags":[]},"children":[{"type":"code","lang":"python","executable":true,"value":"G = nx.karate_club_graph()\nfig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 3, figsize=(18, 12))\n\nfor i, seed in enumerate([0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5]):\n    pos = nx.layout.spring_layout(G, seed=seed)\n    x = i // 3\n    y = i % 3\n    nx.draw(G, with_labels=True, node_color=[G.degree(n) for n in G.nodes()],\n           pos=pos, ax=axes[x, y], alpha=0.7)\n    axes[x, y].set_title(f\"Spring layout, seed={seed}\")\n\n#plt.savefig(\"networkx_graph_spring_layouts_random.png\", dpi=200, bbox_inches=\"tight\")    \nplt.show()","visibility":"hide","key":"aamtLetjRE"},{"type":"outputs","id":"T7BhIaS5HJlg3bRKWDgSE","children":[{"type":"output","jupyter_data":{"output_type":"display_data","metadata":{},"data":{"image/png":{"content_type":"image/png","hash":"ccb775d68ba979b0f1d1a5bb13896771","path":"/build/ccb775d68ba979b0f1d1a5bb13896771.png"},"text/plain":{"content":"<Figure size 1800x1200 with 6 Axes>","content_type":"text/plain"}}},"children":[],"key":"VHNnsweVxy"}],"visibility":"show","key":"zgsBMHgv5w"}],"visibility":"show","key":"NdtBEgZBz5"},{"type":"block","kind":"notebook-content","children":[{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Interactive Plots","position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"key":"Yyq78CW4RI"}],"identifier":"interactive-plots","label":"Interactive Plots","html_id":"interactive-plots","implicit":true,"key":"H1D8CigTVG"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":2,"column":1},"end":{"line":2,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"As just shown in the figure above, the position of nodes is usually neither static nor fixed. Exceptions are graphs that have a corresponding, physical counterpart, such as locations on a geographic map.","position":{"start":{"line":2,"column":1},"end":{"line":2,"column":1}},"key":"QxQvjmqpMA"}],"key":"F51Pcw1l0Y"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":4,"column":1},"end":{"line":4,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"When working with network data, we often quickly reach a point where static visualizations (such as all the graphs plotted in this section so far) are no longer good enough.","position":{"start":{"line":4,"column":1},"end":{"line":4,"column":1}},"key":"m3oW35rwjy"}],"key":"YxT7scga2A"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":6,"column":1},"end":{"line":6,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"In Python, there are a few ways to visualize the networks dynamically using special plotting libraries. One of them is ","position":{"start":{"line":6,"column":1},"end":{"line":6,"column":1}},"key":"WCtIf8zF0o"},{"type":"link","url":"https://pyvis.readthedocs.io/en/latest/index.html","position":{"start":{"line":6,"column":1},"end":{"line":6,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"inlineCode","value":"pyvis","position":{"start":{"line":6,"column":1},"end":{"line":6,"column":1}},"key":"Z36QtvbcWv"}],"urlSource":"https://pyvis.readthedocs.io/en/latest/index.html","key":"squFhOfdlA"},{"type":"text","value":". Here is an example of how to plot the karate network using pyvis:","position":{"start":{"line":6,"column":1},"end":{"line":6,"column":1}},"key":"ihgqNEFLiB"}],"key":"MvzoPtJo41"}],"key":"aD56Dj59KK"},{"type":"block","kind":"notebook-code","children":[{"type":"code","lang":"python","executable":true,"value":"from pyvis.network import Network\n\n# Create a pyvis Network object\nnet = Network(height = \"700px\", width = \"700px\", notebook = True, cdn_resources='remote')\n\nnode_sizes = [2 * G.degree(n) for n in G.nodes()]\n            \n# Set node sizes and colors\nfor i, name in enumerate(G.nodes):\n    G.nodes[name]['size'] = node_sizes[i]\n    G.nodes[name]['color'] = \"lightblue\" if name == 0 or name == 33 else \"crimson\"\n\n# Set edge color\nfor i in G.edges:\n    G.edges[i]['color'] = \"grey\"\n\nnet.from_nx(G)\nnet.show('out1.html')","key":"DSyMDWol6n"},{"type":"outputs","id":"bEi-8pI_IMq7h6x-ACBcw","childre